Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: Current evaluation methodologies in code generation predominantly rely on exact match (e.g., pass@k) or syntactic similarity metrics, which inherently favor precision—only code that exactly passes all test cases is considered correct. However, this overlooks functionally valid solutions that may differ in implementation but behave equivalently under the problem's specification. In safety-critical or exploratory programming contexts, missing such valid solutions (i.e., low recall) can be more detrimental than accepting a few spurious ones. Inspired by Paper 1’s use of semantic hashing for diversity and Paper 2’s focus on functional overlap between solution clusters, I propose a novel scoring mechanism that shifts the evaluation paradigm toward recall by identifying behavioral equivalence through abstracted execution signatures. Unlike SRank, which reranks based on functional overlap to improve precision, our method explicitly maximizes recall by clustering semantically equivalent programs—even those with divergent syntax—and assigning partial credit accordingly. This approach integrates semantic hashing (à la COD3S) with dynamic analysis to construct "behavioral fingerprints" of generated code, enabling fine-grained recognition of correct-but-different implementations. Furthermore, we introduce a diversity-aware recall metric that rewards systems not only for generating correct outputs but also for exploring multiple distinct solution paths, aligning better with human problem-solving patterns observed in Paper 3. The key innovation lies in reframing evaluation as a recall-optimized, semantics-driven process rather than a binary correctness check, thereby encouraging models to explore broader solution spaces without penalizing creative yet correct alternatives.

