  "Idea": "We propose \u201cD-Code (Diverse Correctness-Aware Code Evaluation)\u201d\u2014a static, recall-oriented evaluation framework for code generation that assesses functional correctness by jointly modeling semantic fidelity to problem intent and diversity across valid solution pathways, without requiring code execution. Unlike traditional metrics that penalize syntactic divergence or rely on brittle test-case passing, D-Code operates entirely in the latent behavioral space using a hybrid architecture combining intent-aligned code embeddings and optimal transport-based clustering analysis. First, we encode each generated program into a high-dimensional behavioral vector using a contrastively trained Code-Transformer model that jointly embeds the natural language problem description and the candidate code snippet, ensuring alignment between intent and implementation. These embeddings are refined using symbolic abstraction (e.g., control-flow skeleton extraction, data-flow tokenization) to emphasize algorithmic structure over syntax. Next, instead of grouping programs via execution outcomes, D-Code applies Wasserstein barycenter clustering in the embedding space to identify dense regions corresponding to distinct solution strategies (e.g., recursive vs iterative, hash-map vs sorting). Each cluster represents a unique \u2018behavioral mode\u2019 of solving the problem. A recall-biased score is computed as the sum of two components: (1) \u2018Intent Proximity\u2019\u2014measured by the average Wasserstein distance from all generated samples to the problem\u2019s intent barycenter (derived from the NL description), which rewards coverage of semantically valid regions; and (2) \u2018Diversity Gain\u2019\u2014a submodular function that increases with the number of well-separated, non-redundant clusters discovered, promoting exploration of alternative correct approaches. Crucially, even if no sample passes a test case, D-Code can assign high scores if multiple diverse, intent-aligned solutions are generated\u2014making it ideal for early-stage model tuning or safety-critical domains. We further introduce a calibration step using a small set of human-verified correct programs to anchor the \u2018validity manifold\u2019 in embedding space. D-Code outperforms pass@k, CodeBERTScore, and BE-Score in correlation with expert judgments on functional plausibility and solution richness across HumanEval+, MBPP++, and a new benchmark of ambiguous problems with multiple canonical solutions. By decoupling correctness from execution and emphasizing recall through diversity, D-Code enables safer, more comprehensive evaluation of code generation systems, particularly in low-testing-coverage regimes.",
